\title{nanoGPT provides a simplified, highly optimized, and readable PyTorch implementation of the GPT architecture, enabling efficient training and finetuning of models up to GPT-2 scale with minimal boilerplate code}
\author{PaperPilot}
\date{Drafted by PaperPilot for \emph{EMNLP 2026} on 2026-05-23}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
We present nanoGPT, a minimal yet highly optimized PyTorch implementation of the GPT architecture designed to lower the barrier to training and finetuning medium-scale language models. Despite the proliferation of large language model research, accessible reference implementations that balance readability with computational efficiency remain scarce, impeding rapid prototyping and empirical investigation. nanoGPT addresses this gap by providing a clean, well-documented codebase that leverages modern PyTorch capabilities—including Distributed Data Parallel training, mixed-precision arithmetic, and ahead-of-time compilation via torch.compile()—to achieve strong practical performance without sacrificing interpretability. The implementation supports both training from scratch on corpora such as OpenWebText and finetuning from released GPT-2 checkpoints. Empirically, nanoGPT reproduces GPT-2 (124M parameters) at a validation loss of approximately 2.85 on OpenWebText within four days on an eight-GPU A100 node, while smaller character-level models trained on Shakespeare reach a validation loss of 1.47 in under three minutes on a single GPU. Compiler-driven optimizations yield iteration time reductions exceeding 45%. Accompanying notebooks provide theoretical analyses of parameter counts and floating-point operation scaling, supporting reproducible empirical study of language model behavior across scales.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
## Introduction

The proliferation of large language models has fundamentally reshaped the landscape of natural language processing, yet the practical infrastructure required to train and fine-tune such models remains a persistent barrier to entry for a substantial portion of the research community. Even models at the medium scale—on the order of hundreds of millions of parameters—impose considerable engineering overhead, demanding careful orchestration of distributed training, memory-efficient computation, and hardware-aware optimization. This friction between theoretical accessibility and practical reproducibility has created an asymmetry in the field: while the architectural principles underlying models such as GPT-2 are well understood, the ability to rapidly instantiate, modify, and experiment with these models from first principles is far from universal. Lowering this barrier is not merely a matter of convenience; it directly enables a broader and more diverse set of researchers to contribute empirical findings, stress-test modeling assumptions, and iterate on novel hypotheses at meaningful scale.

Existing open-source implementations of transformer-based language models have made important strides toward democratizing access, yet they frequently introduce substantial complexity in the form of sprawling codebases, opaque abstraction layers, and dependencies on specialized training frameworks. Such designs, while appropriate for production-scale deployments, obscure the relationship between architectural choices and empirical outcomes, making them poorly suited for pedagogical use or rapid experimental iteration. Furthermore, many available implementations do not cleanly separate concerns between model definition, data processing, and training logic, complicating efforts to isolate and study individual components. The result is that reproducibility of foundational results—a cornerstone of empirical NLP research—often requires significant reverse-engineering effort before meaningful experimentation can begin.

In this work, we present nanoGPT, a minimalist yet fully capable PyTorch implementation of the GPT architecture designed to prioritize readability, reproducibility, and computational efficiency in equal measure. Our implementation reproduces GPT-2 (124M parameters) on OpenWebText, achieving a validation loss of approximately 2.85 within a tractable training budget, while also supporting lightweight character-level experiments completable in minutes on a single GPU. By integrating modern PyTorch capabilities—including Distributed Data Parallel training, mixed-precision arithmetic, and compilation-based acceleration—nanoGPT demonstrates that accessibility and performance need not be in tension, offering the community a transparent and empirically grounded foundation for language modeling research.

\section{Related Work}
## Related Work

**Transformer-based Language Model Training and Finetuning.** The GPT architecture has become a foundational paradigm for language modeling, and a growing body of work explores efficient strategies for adapting pre-trained models to downstream tasks. Instruction tuning has emerged as a particularly effective finetuning paradigm: \cite{arxiv_2304_03277} demonstrates that GPT-4-generated instruction-following data can dramatically improve zero-shot generalization, while \cite{arxiv_2304_12244} proposes complexity-driven data augmentation to help models handle more nuanced instructions. These works underscore the practical importance of accessible, reproducible training pipelines—precisely the gap that nanoGPT addresses—since iterating on finetuning strategies requires rapid experimentation at manageable computational cost.

**Efficient and Lightweight Model Implementations.** Reducing the overhead of training and inference is a central concern for the NLP community. \cite{arxiv_2302_04725} investigates lightweight Transformer architectures for clinical NLP, showing that smaller, well-optimized models can remain competitive with large general-purpose ones when training resources are constrained. Similarly, \cite{arxiv_2410_00531} tackles the challenge of serving large-scale LLMs on resource-limited edge devices, highlighting that architectural simplicity and inference efficiency are not merely academic concerns but practical necessities for broad deployment. nanoGPT's emphasis on readability and `torch.compile()`-driven speedups aligns with this line of inquiry.

**Data Efficiency and Benchmark Evaluation.** Recent studies challenge the assumption that more data and larger instruction sets always yield better models. \cite{arxiv_2311_13133} demonstrates that smaller, curated instruction datasets can match or exceed the performance of models trained on far larger corpora, motivating careful dataset curation in training pipelines. Domain-specific evaluation has also gained traction: \cite{arxiv_2310_04793} benchmarks open-source LLMs on financial instruction-following tasks, illustrating that reproducing and evaluating GPT-scale models in specialized settings requires precisely the kind of lightweight, modifiable infrastructure nanoGPT provides. Together, these threads motivate simplified, transparent implementations that lower the barrier to controlled empirical study across diverse NLP settings.

\section{Method}
## 3 Method

We develop a streamlined PyTorch implementation of the GPT architecture designed to balance readability, reproducibility, and computational efficiency at medium model scales. Our approach centers on two core components: a self-contained Transformer-based language model and a general-purpose training pipeline capable of supporting both training from scratch and finetuning from pretrained checkpoints. The model follows the standard GPT design, comprising stacked blocks of causal self-attention and position-wise feed-forward layers with learned positional embeddings. The training pipeline is built around PyTorch's native tooling, leveraging Distributed Data Parallel (DDP) for multi-GPU scaling, automatic mixed-precision (AMP) for memory efficiency, and ahead-of-time compilation via `torch.compile()` to reduce per-iteration overhead. To support diverse experimental settings, we provide data preparation utilities for both a character-level corpus (Shakespeare) and a large web-crawled corpus (OpenWebText), enabling controlled comparisons across data scales and vocabulary granularities. Finetuning is supported by initializing model weights directly from publicly released GPT-2 checkpoints, with the training loop adapted accordingly. Together, these design choices yield a minimal yet fully functional framework within which the empirical training dynamics and scaling behavior of GPT-class models can be systematically studied.

\section{Results}
\emph{Results section drafted from the repository's reported numbers and qualitative findings:}

The implementation successfully reproduces GPT-2 (124M) on OpenWebText, achieving a validation loss of ~2.85 in approximately 4 days on an 8x A100 node. It also demonstrates rapid training of smaller character-level GPTs on Shakespeare, achieving a validation loss of 1.4697 in 3 minutes on a single A100 GPU, and highlights significant speedups (e.g., ~250ms to 135ms per iteration) from `torch.compile()`.

\section{Discussion and Limitations}
\emph{Limitations the repository acknowledges or that follow from the method:}

The repository is explicitly noted as 'very old and deprecated' by its author, with a newer `nanochat` project available. Future work suggested includes investigating FSDP, evaluating zero-shot perplexities on standard benchmarks (e.g., LAMBADA, HELM), and refining finetuning hyperparameters.

